.TH "super" "1" "April 2026" ""
.SH NAME
super \(em process data with SuperSQL queries
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]super\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]command\f[R]
.PP
\f[B]super\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[B]\-c\f[R] \f[I]query\f[R]]
[\f[I]file\f[R] \&...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]super\f[R] executes SuperSQL queries against data from files, URLs,
or standard input, and writes results to standard output or a file.
It operates either as a standalone query engine (detached from any
database) or as the entry point to a hierarchy of sub\-commands for
database management, query compilation, and developer tooling.
.PP
When invoked without a sub\-command, \f[B]super\f[R] runs the query
engine against the specified inputs.
Inputs may be specified as command\-line path arguments or referenced
within the query itself using a \f[B]from\f[R] operator or SQL FROM
clause.
When the path argument is \f[B]\-\f[R], input is read from standard
input.
HTTP, HTTPS, and S3 URLs are also accepted as paths.
.PP
If no query is provided, inputs are scanned and emitted in the output
format specified by \f[B]\-f\f[R].
If no input is provided, the query receives a single \f[B]null\f[R]
value, enabling calculator\-style use.
.PP
Input formats are detected automatically by file extension or by
sampling the data.
The \f[B]line\f[R] format cannot be auto\-detected and must be requested
explicitly with \f[B]\-i line\f[R].
Parquet and CSUP require seekable input and cannot be read from standard
input.
.PP
When writing to a terminal, the default output format is SUP.
Otherwise, it is BSUP.
These defaults are overridden by \f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\-s\f[R], or
\f[B]\-S\f[R].
.PP
Multiple \f[B]\-c\f[R] and \f[B]\-I\f[R] options may be combined; their
text is concatenated in left\-to\-right order with intervening newlines.
.SS Errors
Fatal errors (e.g., file not found, filesystem full) cause
\f[B]super\f[R] to exit immediately.
Runtime errors produced by the query itself do not halt execution;
instead they appear as first\-class error values interleaved with valid
output in the result stream.
Use the \f[B]is_error\f[R] function to identify and filter these values.
.SS Debugging
Run \f[B]super \-C \-c\f[R] \f[I]query\f[R] to display the parsed,
canonical form of a query without executing it.
This is useful for understanding how shorthand syntax is expanded \(em
for example, bare expressions become implied \f[B]where\f[R] or
\f[B]put\f[R] operators.
The \f[B]debug\f[R] operator can be inserted anywhere in a pipeline to
trace intermediate values to standard error.
