.SH OUTPUT
Output originates in super\-structured form and is serialized to the
requested format.
Supported output formats are: \f[CR]arrows\f[R], \f[CR]bsup\f[R],
\f[CR]csup\f[R], \f[CR]csv\f[R], \f[CR]db\f[R], \f[CR]json\f[R],
\f[CR]jsup\f[R], \f[CR]line\f[R], \f[CR]parquet\f[R], \f[CR]sup\f[R],
\f[CR]table\f[R], \f[CR]tsv\f[R], \f[CR]zeek\f[R].
.PP
When stdout is a terminal, the default format is SUP; otherwise BSUP.
Override with \f[B]\-f\f[R], \f[B]\-s\f[R], or \f[B]\-S\f[R].
.PP
Schema\-rigid formats (Arrow, Parquet) require all output values to
conform to a single schema.
To write heterogeneous super\-structured data to such formats, either
apply the \f[B]fuse\f[R] or \f[B]blend\f[R] operator to unify types, or
use \f[B]\-split\f[R] to write one file per type.
Attempting to write multiple record types to a single Parquet file
without fusion produces an error.
.PP
The \f[CR]line\f[R] output format emits one value per line.
String values are printed as\-is with escape sequences rendered as their
native characters.
Non\-string values are formatted as SUP.
.PP
The \f[CR]db\f[R] format pretty\-prints lake metadata and is the default
for many \f[CR]super db\f[R] sub\-commands.
.SH ERRORS
Fatal I/O errors terminate the process immediately with a non\-zero exit
status.
Query runtime errors produce first\-class error values in the output
stream rather than halting execution.
These can be detected with the \f[B]is_error\f[R] function and inspected
or re\-wrapped for stack\-trace\-like diagnostics.
.SH EXAMPLES
Query a CSV, JSON, or Parquet file using SuperSQL:
.IP
.EX
super \-c \(dqSELECT * FROM file.[csv|csv.gz|json|json.gz|parquet]\(dq
.EE
.PP
Run a SuperSQL query sourced from an input file:
.IP
.EX
super \-I path/to/query.sql
.EE
.PP
Pretty\-print a sample value as super\-structured data:
.IP
.EX
super \-S \-c \(dqlimit 1\(dq file.[csv|csv.gz|json|json.gz|parquet]
.EE
.PP
Compute a histogram of the \(lqdata shapes\(rq in a JSON file:
.IP
.EX
super \-c \(dqcount() by typeof(this)\(dq file.json
.EE
.PP
Display a sample value of each \(lqshape\(rq of JSON data:
.IP
.EX
super \-c \(dqany(this) by typeof(this) | values any\(dq file.json
.EE
.PP
Search Parquet files easily and efficiently without schema handcuffs:
.IP
.EX
super *.parquet > all.bsup
super \-c \(dq? search keywords | other pipe processing\(dq all.bsup
.EE
.PP
Read a CSV from stdin, process with a query, and write to stdout:
.IP
.EX
cat input.csv | super \-f csv \-c <query> \-
.EE
.PP
Fuse JSON data into a unified schema and output as Parquet:
.IP
.EX
super \-f parquet \-o out.parquet \-c fuse file.json
.EE
.PP
Run as a calculator:
.IP
.EX
super \-c \(dq1.+(1/2.)+(1/3.)+(1/4.)\(dq
.EE
.PP
Search all values in a database pool called logs for keyword
\(lqalert\(rq and level >= 2:
.IP
.EX
super db \-c \(dqfrom logs | ? alert level >= 2\(dq
.EE
.PP
Traverse nested data with recursive functions and re\-entrant
subqueries:
.IP
.EX
super \-c \(aq
fn walk(node, visit):
  case kind(node)
  when \(dqarray\(dq then
    [unnest node | walk(this, visit)]
  when \(dqrecord\(dq then
    unflatten([unnest flatten(node) | {key,value:walk(value, visit)}])
  when \(dqunion\(dq then
    walk(under(node), visit)
  else visit(node)
  end
fn addOne(node): case typeof(node) when <int64> then node+1 else node end
values 1, [1,2,3], [{x:[1,\(dqfoo\(dq]},{y:2}]
| values walk(this, &addOne)
\(aq
.EE
.PP
Handle and wrap errors in a SuperSQL pipeline:
.IP
.EX
\&... | super \-c \(dq
switch is_error(this) (
    case true ( values error({message:\(rs\(dqerror into stage N\(rs\(dq, on:this}) )
    default (
        <non\-error processing here>
        ...
    )
)
\(dq
| ...
.EE
.PP
Embed a pipe query search in a SQL FROM clause:
.IP
.EX
super \-c \(dq
SELECT union(type) as kinds, network_of(srcip) as net
FROM ( from logs.json | ? example.com AND urgent )
WHERE message_length > 100
GROUP BY net
\(dq
.EE
.PP
Or write this as a pure pipe query:
.IP
.EX
super \-c \(dq
from logs.json
| ? example.com AND urgent
| message_length > 100
| kinds:=union(type), net:=network_of(srcip) by net
\(dq
.EE
